egger, and John Rawls; Shuster reveals how various contemporary television series engage deeply with aesthetic and philosophical issues in modernism and modernity. What unifies the aesthetic and philosophical ambitions of new television is a commitment to portraying and exploring the family as the last site of political possibility in a world otherwise bereft of any other sources of traditional authority; consequently, at the heart of new television are profound political stakes.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aFamilies on television. 0aTelevision serieszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aTelevision series--United States--History and criticism. 4aHannah Arendt. 4aMartin Heidegger. 4aStanley Cavell. 4aaesthetics. 4anew television. 4aphenomenology. 4aphilosophy of art. 4apolitical philosophy. 4atelevision series. 4atelevision. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226504001423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226504001.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles